com.ampro.robinhood

Class RobinhoodApi

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ampro.robinhood.RobinhoodApi

  • public class RobinhoodApi
extends java.lang.Object

    A RobinhoodApi instance is used as an intermediary between the Robinhood servers and your java/kotlin/whatever application.

    Configuration

    Each API instance contains it's own Configuration which contains information about account tokens and urls (if the API has been logged in).

    • Constructor Detail

      • RobinhoodApi

        public RobinhoodApi()
        Constructor which creates all of the access points to use the API. This constructor does not require the Username and Password, thus giving limited access to the API. See Robinhood Unofficial Documentation at following link to see what can and cannot be used if you do not authorize a user

      • RobinhoodApi

        public RobinhoodApi(java.lang.String username,
                    java.lang.String password)
             throws RobinhoodApiException
        Constructor which creates all of the access points to use the API. This constructor requires both a Username and Password and attempts to authorize the user. On success, the AuthorizationData will be stored in the Configuration instance to be retrieved elsewhere. On failure, an error will be thrown.
        NOTE: This cannot be used with multifactor authorization.
        Parameters:
        username - The user's email (that they use with robinhood)
        password - The user's password
        Throws:
        RobinhoodApiException - If the login failed

    • Method Detail

      • requestAuthData

        public AuthorizationData requestAuthData(java.lang.String email,
                                         java.lang.String password)
        Request AuthorizationData from Robinhood and adds it to the Configuration.
        Parameters:
        email - The email to login with
        password - The password
        Returns:
        The AuthorizationData returned or null if failed. This will wither contain a token or multifactor details.

      • login

        public LoginStatus login(java.lang.String email,
                         java.lang.String password)
        Method which logs a user in given a email and password. This method automatically stores the authorization token in with the instance, allowing any method which requires the token to have immediate access to it. This method is ran if you created the RobinhoodApi class using the constructor with both a email and password, but is available if you wish to get the authorization token again. Usually ran after the user is logged out to refresh the token
        Parameters:
        email - The user's email
        password - The user's password
        Returns:
        LoginStatus.FAILURE if the user could not be logged in. LoginStatus.SUCCESS otherwise

      • loginMultifactor

        public LoginStatus loginMultifactor(java.lang.String email,
                                    java.lang.String password,
                                    java.lang.String code)
        Login with a Multifactor/Two-factor authorization code. This requires the Configuration's AuthorizationData to be set with requestAuthData(String, String)
        Parameters:
        email - The user's email
        password - The user's password
        code - The mfa code
        Returns:
        LoginStatus.FAILURE if the user could not be logged in. LoginStatus.SUCCESS otherwise

        public LoginStatus logUserOut()

        Returns:
        an enum containing either "SUCCESS"or "NOT_LOGGED_IN"

      • getAccountWatchlist

        public java.util.List<Position> getAccountWatchlist()
        Returns a list of Position for each entry on the account's watchlist. If the quantity of the Position is above 0, that means that you have an active position in that stock. All of the other information which can be retrieved from this can be found in the Position page itself
        Returns:
        A list of Position, both held and only watched entities
        Throws:
        NotLoggedInException - If not logged in

      • makeLimitOrder

        public SecurityOrder makeLimitOrder(java.lang.String ticker,
                                    TimeInForce timeInForce,
                                    float limitPrice,
                                    int quantity,
                                    OrderTransactionType orderType)
                             throws TickerNotFoundException
        Method which returns a SecurityOrder after running a LIMIT order given the supplied parameters.
        Parameters:
        ticker - The ticker which the buy or sell order should be performed on
        timeInForce - The Enum representation for when this order should be made
        limitPrice - The price you're willing to accept in a sell, or pay in a buy
        quantity - The number of shares you would like to buy or sell
        orderType - Which type of order is being made. A buy, or sell.
        Returns:
        The SecurityOrder that was made
        Throws:
        TickerNotFoundException - Thrown when the ticker supplied to the method is invalid.
        NotLoggedInException - Thrown when this Robinhood Api instance is not logged into an account. Run the login method first.

      • getQuoteListByTickers

        public java.util.List<TickerQuote> getQuoteListByTickers(java.util.Collection<java.lang.String> tickers)
                                                  throws RequestTooLargeException
        Get a list of security quotes by their tickers. The result is SemiPaginated, which is why this can return a normal List
        Parameters:
        tickers - The tickers to get quotes of (e.g. MSFT, FIT)
        Returns:
        A list of TickerQuoteElements. A value in the list may be null if the ticker was not found on Robinhood.
        Throws:
        RequestTooLargeException - if the collection is longer than 1,630

      • getAllInstruments

        public java.util.List<Instrument> getAllInstruments()
        Get's every Instrument tracked by Robinhood. This method performs several calls to the Robinhood servers and is therefore rather expensive to use. Try to use it sparingly (it's not like it's going to be changing all the time)
        Returns:
        Every Instrument tracked by Robinhood

      • setAuthToken

        @Deprecated
public void setAuthToken(java.lang.String token)
        Deprecated. 
        Method allowing a user to input a token without logging in. It is not suggested you use this unless you have a specific reason where you need to inject a auth token into the instance, generally allowing the system to resolve this token with a username and password is more 'secure'.
